<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Habit and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Herbs to subshrubs; native to southern South America, but naturalized in the Mascarene islands of Mauritius, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Réunion">Reunion</normalizedToken>
, and Rodrigues (
<bibRefCitation author="Croizat, L" journalOrPublisher="Tropical Woods" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" pagination="13 - 15" refId="B19" refString="Croizat, L, 1944. New Euphorbiaceae from the island of Mauritius. Tropical Woods 77: 13 - 15" title="New Euphorbiaceae from the island of Mauritius." volume="77" year="1944">Croizat 1944</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Coode, MJE" editor="Bosser, J" journalOrPublisher="153. Lauracees a 160. Euphorbiacees. The Sugar Industry Research Institute, Mauritius, L'Office de la Recherche Scientifique et Technique Outre-Mer, Paris, and The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="41 - 50" refId="B18" refString="Coode, MJE, 1982. Croton L. In: Bosser, J, Cadet, T, Gueho, J, Marais, W, Eds., Flore des Mascareignes: La Reunion, Maurice, Rodrigues. 153. Lauracees a 160. Euphorbiacees. The Sugar Industry Research Institute, Mauritius, L'Office de la Recherche Scientifique et Technique Outre-Mer, Paris, and The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew: 41 - 50" title="Croton L." volumeTitle="Flore des Mascareignes: La Reunion, Maurice, Rodrigues." year="1982">Coode 1982</bibRefCitation>
), as well as on Mayotte (Grande Terre - Mamoudzou, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kawéni">Kaweni</normalizedToken>
, 9 Sep 2005, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Barthelat &amp; Changama 1504</emphasis>
, K).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Croton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Croton bonplandianus" order="Malpighiales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bonplandianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Croton bonplandianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently the only non-native, naturalized species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Croton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Croton" order="Malpighiales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Croton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Western Indian Ocean Region. Oddly, it is known from Mayotte and the Mascarenes, but it has not yet been observed or collected in Madagascar.
</paragraph>
